// ANGLAIS
$title_en ='Map types';
$content_en = '<h2>Cartogram (or anamorphic map)</h2>';
$content_en .='<p><img src="images/schema_anamorphose.jpg"/></p>';
$content_en .= '<p>In a common way, an anamorphosis is a distorted projection or perspective requiring the viewer to use special devices or occupy a specific vantage point to reconstitute the image. The word is derived from the Greek prefix ana-, meaning back or again, and the word morphe, meaning shape or form. According to Webster dictionary “An anamorphosis is a deformed image that appears in its true shape when viewed in some "unconventional" way”. In cartography we call them “cartograms” or “anamorphic map”. A cartogram is a map in which some thematic mapping variable – such as population or Gross National Product-  is substituted for land area or distance. The geometry or space of the map is distorted in order to convey the information of this alternate variable. We also can describe a cartogram as a type of graphic that depicts attributes of geographic objects as the object\'s area. Because a cartogram does not depict geographic space, but rather changes the size of objects depending on a certain attribute, a cartogram is not a true map. There are two main types of cartograms: area and distance cartograms. An area cartogram is sometimes referred to as a value-by-area map or an iso-demographic map, the latter particularly for a population cartogram, which illustrates the relative sizes of the populations of the countries of the world by scaling the area of each country in proportion to its population; the shape and relative location of each country is retained to as large an extent as possible, but inevitably a large amount of distortion results. A distance cartogram may also be called a central-point cartogram. This form is typically used to show relative travel times and directions from vertices in a network. One of the first cartographers to generate cartograms with the aid of computer visualization was W. Tobler in the 1960s. Different methods are used to design a cartogram. In AIRE atlas, we choose the Gastner et M. E. J. Newman diffusion algorithm. Based on the physical process of the linear gases distribution, this algorithm works according to a calculation of density in a given regular grid which is gradually deformed. Zones with high density are propagated towards zones with low density until the density of every zone is equal to the average density. This algorithm preserves the topology.</p>';
$content_en .=$MenuMapType_en;